    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The p-values, you ask? If your residuals are still behaving like a stampede of angry goblins, your standard errors and p-values are probably unreliable, which is a real problem. Think of it this way: if the errors aren't normally distributed, your confidence intervals and hypothesis tests are based on shaky ground, like a goblin-infested mud pit. You might find your coefficients are statistically significant when they shouldn't be, or vice-versa. It's always best to try and tame the data, but if you can't, consider bootstrapping your standard errors instead of relying on the traditional t-tests. Bootstrapping is like having a whole horde of tiny, unpredictable goblins running simulations to give you a more honest picture of the uncertainty.\n\nIf the *assumption* of normality is violated but your model still has good predictive power (which is often the case in real-world housing data), the model might still be *useful*, but you must be cautious. You're trading statistical purity for practical utility. You could also explore Generalized Linear Models (GLMs), perhaps using a Gamma distribution if your prices are strictly positive and skewed—that's like giving your data a specialized goblin cage that'",
